occurrences.line_text: Assotted had his sense, or dazed was his eie.
Him bet so sore, that life and sense did much dismay.
Whilest trembling horrour did his sense assayle,
Nor sense of man so coy and curious nice,
But there it present was, and did fraile sense entice.
So did the sight thereof their sense dismay,
A doubtfull sense of things, not so well seene, as felt.
The Ladie hearkning to his sensefull speach,
Whose sensefull words empierst his hart so neare,
Now let the stony dart of senselesse cold
The senselesse corse appointed for the graue.
Being diffused through the senselesse truncke,
Whiles sad Pyrrochles lies on senselesse ground,
Wherewith astonisht, still he stood, as senselesse stone.
In senselesse dreame; which sight at first him sore aghast.
And all his senses drowned in deepe senselesse waue.
The lumpish corse vnto the senselesse grownd;
Inglorious now lies in senselesse swownd,
But senselesse stood, like to a mazed steare,
Vnto the earth, and lay long while in senselesse swowne.
And their faint harts with senselesse horrour queld,
Which tombling downe vpon the senselesse ground,
Of senselesse words, which nature did him teach,
That to the ground he fell in senselesse swone:
And falleth downe to ground like senselesse thing,
That all my senses were bereaued quight:
Their frayle amazed senses did confound:
And all his senses were with suddeine dread dismayd.
Became starke blind, and all his senses daz'd,
It dimmes the dazed eyen, and daunts the senses quight.
The deadly dint his dulled senses all dismaid.
That all his senses seemd bereft attone:
Thus when she had his eyes and senses fed
And all his senses were with deadly fit opprest.
And all his senses drowned in deepe senselesse waue.
That all their senses filled with affright,
Which Guyons senses softly tickeled,
My senses lulled are in slomber of delight.
With double senses, and with false debate,
Her goodly port, and to their senses vild,
Least his fraile senses were emperisht quight,
How she might heale her sonne, whose senses were decayd.
And fild his senses with abashment great;
And all her senses with abashment quite were quayld.
To shrowd themselues, whiles sleepe their senses did inuade.
The feeble senses wholly did confound,
The hammers sound his senses did molest;
That all his senses did full soone arrest:
He saw his senses straunge astonishment,
In sad despaire, and all thy senses swowned
Like lyfull heat to nummed senses brought,
So sensibly compyld, that in the same
Her captiue to his sensuall desire,
To slug in slouth and sensuall delights,
With one sweet drop of sensuall delight:
Armed with darts of sensuall delight,
Where Pleasure dwelles in sensuall delights,
And swimming deepe in sensuall desires,
And poured forth in sensuall delight,
It stirreth vp to sensuall desire,
Yet all that might not slake her sensuall desyre.
Hither (quoth he) me Archimago sent,
A fit false dreame, that can delude the sleepers sent.
And damned sprights sent forth to make ill men aghast.
Cursing high Ioue, the which them thither sent.
In euill houre thy foes thee hither sent,
Through which he sent his voyce, and lowd did call
Me hither sent, for cause to me vnghest,
And streightway sent with carefull diligence,
And from his wide deuouring ouen sent
That sent to heauen the ecchoed report
Whom all admired, as from heauen sent,
To whom the Redcrosse knight this answere sent,
My Lord (quoth he) me sent, and streight behight
Was sent to Aganip of Celtica.
Of Rome againe, who hither hastly sent
Which when the Romanes heard, they hither sent
He sent to Germanie, straunge aid to reare,
With which at him a cruell shaft he sent:
Or yuory into the waues were sent;
But the captiu'd Acrasia he sent,
Which forth he sent with felonous despight,
Ne bubbling roundell they behind them sent;
And sent in haste for Tryphon, to apply
Of hunter swift, and sent of houndes trew.
Anone one sent out of the thicket neare
That headlesse him into the foord he sent:
She was well pleasd, and forth her damzels sent,
To search the God of loue, her Nymphes she sent
Or sent into the chaungefull world againe,
Daily they grow, and daily forth are sent
Late forth she sent, she backe returning spyde,
And sent close messages of loue to her at will.
She sent at him one firie dart, whose hed
Gratious respect, thy wife shall backe be sent,
And of the bloodie feast, which sent away
That to Sir Paridell these words he sent;
They sent that Squire afore, to vnderstand,
Conceiued by a ring, which she him sent,
Were sent, that seemed death in them to beare,
So thicke they fell, and forcibly were sent,
Towards them driuing like a storme out sent.
Sent forth their Squire to haue them both descride,
About the house, at sent of stranger guest:
She sent an arrow forth with mighty draught,
Onely few ruefull lookes vnto her sent,
But noysome breath, and poysnous spirit sent
No sooner sayd, but streight he after sent
Therefore he Talus to them sent, t'inquire
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
His mighty hand to shend, he Talus sent
And sent them home to tell a piteous tale,
Vnto those warlike Knights she warning sent.
And sent her winged thoughts, more swift then wind,
That it was one sent from her loue indeede.
So me in message vnto her she sent,
When I was gone, soone after me she sent
Vnto his scornefull Lady, that for her had sent.
And sent to him a Page, that mote direct his way.
Which when he saw, his yron man he sent,
Sent by their mother, who a widow was,
Therefore these two, her eldest sonnes she sent,
His carkasse tumbling on the threshold, sent
And sent redresse thereof by this braue Briton Knight.
And now he hath this troupe of villains sent,
All hidden crimes, through all that realme he sent,
Into this wicked world he forth was sent,
He sent to her his basenet, as a faithfull band.
Whose fellow he before had sent apart;
And sent me, where him list, instructed for to bee.
To whose wise read she hearkning, sent me streight
They sent that Blatant Beast to be a baite,
His mindes sad message backe vnto him sent;
That since by grace of God she there was sent,
By righteous sentence of th'Almighties law:
Which proudly did impugne her sentence iust.
And then you shall my sentence vnderstand.
When he his sentence thus pronounced had,
Saues Serena, whilest Calepine
The faire Serena (so his Lady hight)
Serena full of dolorous dismay,
About the sad Serena things to dight,
With that aloude the faire Serena cryde
Mongst which, Serena did to him relate
Aye me (sayd then Serena sighing sore)
The faire Serena, when she saw him fall
Serena, found of Saluages,
Of faire Serena, who as earst you heard,
As he to seeke Serena through the woods did roue.
But faire Serene all night could take no rest,
Which faire Serene to him deliuered had,
When as the gentle Squire, with faire Serene,
Haile good Sir Sergis, truest Knight aliue,
But now aread, Sir Sergis, how long space,
But yet old Sergis did so well him paine,
Halfe like a serpent horribly displaide,
In which a Serpent did himselfe enfold,
And like a Serpent to the Thracian mayd.
The cursed Serpent, though she hungrily
Her fruitfull cursed spawne of serpents small,
About the which two Serpents weren wound,
Like as the Basiliske of serpents seede,
The tongues of Serpents with three forked stings,
But her fierce seruant full of kingly awe
And makes it seruant to her basest part:
The carefull seruant, striuing with his raging Lord.
In which a gracious seruant pictured
In which the sword was seruant vnto right;
To be her thrall, his fellow seruant vild;
That with his seruant Trompart houerd there,
The seruant of Admetus cowheard vile,
And bad his seruant Talus to inuent
And of her seruant make her souerayne Lord:
His trustie sword, the seruant of his might,
As ignoraunt of seruants bad abuse,
In which his worke he had sixe seruants prest,
Of PhÃ¦dria, thine owne fellow seruaunt;
Proffer thy giftes, and fitter seruaunts entertaine.
Doth blesse her seruaunts, and them high aduaunce.
That for his trusty seruaunts doth so strongly fight.
The huge seas vnder her t'obay her seruaunts law.
Long I her seru'd, and found her faithfull still,
And with fresh courage on the victour seru'd:
And seru'd of all things that mote needfull bee;
Then serue his Ladies loue, and wast in pleasures vayne.
But to the wood she goes, to serue her turne,
And sold thy selfe to serue Duessa vilde,
And her to serue six yeares in warlike wize,
To serue againe his soueraine Elfin Queene,
To serue at court in view of vaunting eye;
To serue his Lemans loue: for he, by kind,
For thou to serue Acrasia thy selfe doest vaunt.
Both slow and swift a like do serue my tourne,
Till season serue new passage to assay;
But if for me ye fight, or me will serue,
Wherefore if me thou deigne to serue and sew,
To serue to wicked man, to serue his wicked foe.
To serue to wicked man, to serue his wicked foe.
How that straunge sword refusd, to serue his need,
To serue that Queene with all my powre and might.
Do serue their turnes: here I a while must stay,
Dye rather, dye, and dying do her serue,
Dying her serue, and liuing her adore;
To her, to whom the heauens do serue and sew?
Whom so she fittest finds to serue her lust,
That gentle Lady, whom I loue and serue,
Because his sinfull lust she would not serue,
And those same cursed seedes doe also serue
Therefore he her did court, did serue, did wooe,
For he me seemes most fit the faire to serue,
With murmure soft, that seem'd to serue the workmans will.
To serue, for want of other meete reward,
To serue the lowly vassall of her might,
But none she found so fit to serue that turne,
To serue her so, as she the rest had bound.
Doe serue a Queene, that not far hence doth wone,
And Idols serues; so let his Idols serue the Elfe.
Not so; (quoth he) for yet when time doth serue,
And faithfully did serue both day and night,
And serue their owne necessities with others need.
Did spred it selfe, to serue to all delight,
To serue the vengeaunce of his wrathfull will;
And made vnfit to serue his lawlesse mindes behest.
Him faild thereto, and serued not his need,
Where they were serued with all sumptuous fare,
Serued a gentle Lady of great sway,
He nould be clogd. So had he serued many one.
The winde and weather serued them so well,
And noblest she, that serued is of noblest knight.
But let vs hence depart, whilest wether serues and wind.
For time yet serues that I the same refuse,
Serues her, as any Princesse vnder sky,
And Idols serues; so let his Idols serue the Elfe.
The saluage serues Matilda well
Such homely what, as serues the simple clowne,
A-waite whereto their seruice he applyes,
Now a loose Leman to vile seruice bound:
With humble seruice to her will prepard:
My faithfull seruice, that by land and seas
Like to an holy Monck, the seruice to begin.
To her makes present of his seruice seene:
To do their seruice to Syluanus old,
My simple selfe, and seruice euermore;
Their life to seruice of high heauens king
And doen their seruice to that soueraigne Dame,
Well worthy doest thy seruice for her grace,
To be her Squire, and do her seruice well aguisd.
And th'others pleasing seruice to abate,
To her I homage and my seruice owe,
By faithfull seruice, and meet amenance,
That seruice well. Her yellow golden heare
Offring his seruice, and his dearest life
Shall doe vnto her seruice neuer to remoue.
Ne to your Lady will I seruice done,
And her knights seruice ought, to hold of her in fee.
With which the stubborn feends he to his seruice bound.
What seruice may I do vnto thee meete,
No seruice, bu tthy safety and ayd;
Dye rather, dye, then euer from her seruice swerue.
But foolish boy, what bootes thy seruice bace
The loue and seruice of the basest crew?
Yet neuer learned he such seruice, till that day.
I might do seruice vnto gentle Dames,
So well I to faire Ladies seruice did,
That hast a thanklesse seruice on thee ta'ne,
Vnfit faire Ladies seruice to supply;
And timely seruice to her pleasures meet
That hath himselfe vnto such seruice sold,
He did her seruice dewtifull, and sewed
Her loue, her seruice, and her vtmost wealth.
For which no seruice she too much esteemed,
Yet he to her did dayly seruice more,
And to her seruice bind each liuing creature;
And she most fit his seruice doth deserue,
And with meeke seruice and much suit did lay
Of Kings and Keasars, to thy seruice bound,
No seruice lothsome to a gentle kind;
And all the seruice of the bodie frame,
And with meet seruice waited him about;
To doe their duefull seruice, as to them befell.
To doe her seruice, so as I am bond.
The goodly seruice, the deuicefull sights,
Which didst that seruice vnto Florimell.
And put to that base seruice of her band,
To be her thrall, and seruice her afford.
And eke with gratefull seruice me right well apay.
So praying him t'accept her seruice euermore.
Offred his seruice to disarme the Knight;
Himselfe and seruice to her offered,
For Ladies seruice, and for loues delight,
The noble ympe of such new seruice fayne,
Which wont doe suit and seruice to his might;
And sude and sought with all the seruice dew:
Ne euer had such knightly seruice seene,
All dewfull seruice voide of thoughts imp[u]re:
With humble seruice, and with daily sute,
With dayly seruice and attendance dew,
Not good nor seruiceable else for ought,
Of comely seruices, or courtly trayne?
And courtly seruices tooke no delight,
That vnto Venus seruices was sold.
For ill your goddesse seruices are drest
After long suit and weary seruicis,
Her seruile beast yet would not leaue her so,
Then them to haue my selfe, and be their seruile sclaue.
Good turnes be counted, as a seruile bond,
But he had brought it now in seruile bond,
Of seruile yoke, that nobler harts repine.
Seruing th'ambitious will of Augustine,
And seruing her in her malitious vse,
Seruing proud Radigund with true subiection;
By this the Northerne wagoner had set
And high hath set his throne, where Tiberis doth pas.
He set her on her steede, and forward forth did beare.
And triple crowne set on her head full hye,
He set the false Duessa, for more aw and dread.
Who when her eyes she on the Dwarf had set,
As two broad Beacons, set in open fields,
Those glaring lampes were set, that made a dreadfull shade.
And high her burning torch set vp in heauen bright.
Then on her head they set a girland greene,
By certaine signes here set in sundry place
Which on your shield is set for ornament:
She set her downe to weepe for sore constraint,
Proudly to prune, and set on euery side,
And set in highest seat of dignitee,
To chaunge thy will, and set Occasion free,
Emongst wide waues set, like a litle nest,
She set beside, laying his head disarm'd
Nine was the circle set in heauens place,
It might breake out, and set the whole on fire,
And set them forth, as well he could deuise.
Two goodly Beacons, set in watches stead,
Were made, and set in siluer sockets bright,
Amidst them all he in a chaire was set,
To which whiles absent he his mind did set,
The other fiue, fiue sundry wayes he set,
A mighty Mazer bowle of wine was set,
And all the margent round about was set,
All my delight on deedes of armes is set,
Imperious Loue hath highest set his throne,
Not so th'Arabian Myrrhe did set her mind;
And set her by to watch, and set her by to weepe.
And set her by to watch, and set her by to weepe.
All her delight is set on Marinell;
Mote algates passe; for thy, themselues they set
They did him set thereon, and forthwith them conuayd.
Her selfe she set, and comfortably cheard;
Your glory set, to chace the saluage beasts,
Ne needs there Gardiner to set, or sow,
Set by it selfe, and ranckt in comely rew:
Of many wretches set his triumphes hye,
He set vpon her Palfrey tired lame,
In stead of eyes two burning lampes she set
Vpon his Courser set the louely lode,
But all his mind is set on mucky pelfe,
On which their eies and harts were wholly set,
That did her win and free from chalenge set:
And set it all on fire by force vnknowen,
And Paridell her scornd, and set at nought,
The perilous present stownd, in which their liues were set.
The day was set, that all might vnderstand,
Was set, to see the fortune of that fray,
And equall armes himselfe did forward set.
Together with this Hag beside her set,
And hauing it about her middle set,
First in the midst to set that fayrest Dame,
For soone as she them saw to discord set,
True loue and faithfull friendship, she by her did set.
Who lay the whiles in swoune, full sadly set,
Fearing least if she should him freely set,
And by the rest did set in sumptuous chaire,
And louers life forth set.
That euer were on earth, all were they set together.
An hundred Altars round about were set,
In which were many towres and castels set,
And on his steed her set, to beare her out of sight.
First in one ballance set the true aside.
But set the truth and set the right aside,
But set the truth and set the right aside,
Of which th'one halfe vpon himselfe did set,
To set afresh on all the other crew.
Then did he set her by that snowy one,
Like the true saint beside the image set,
Soone as the gates were open to them set,
With froward will doth set him selfe to weepe;
One foote was set vppon the Crocodile,
Who seeing her approch gan forward set,
He hath set vp, and him his God hath named;
And set a Seneschall of dreaded might,
Who through his yeares long since aside had set
Did set vpon those troupes with all his powre and might.
But Talus sternely did vpon them set,
And there arriu'd againe, whence forth he set,
By the way side being together set,
Thereto the Blatant beast by them set on
Did set vppon vs flying both for feare:
That mote thy kindled courage set on fire,
So seldome seene, that one in basenesse set
Being vnarm'd, and set in secret shade.
By straunge occasion, that here needs forth be set.
Vpon him set, of perill nought adrad,
Who seeing one in so great daunger set
Vpon a mangy iade vnmeetely set,
And in some stable neare did set him vp to feede.
His foot he set on his vile necke, in signe
Who therewith flesht, vpon him set anew,
He in his necke had set his foote with fell disdaine.
The Damzell was before the altar set,
Tooke Coridon, and set him in his place,
And set his rest amongst the rusticke sort,
Of such false blisse, as there is set for stales,
Were brought vnto their Captaine, who was set
All set with yron teeth in raunges twaine,
Is setled there in sure establishment;
These paires of friends in peace and setled rest,
May nought at all their setled mindes remoue,
There whilest he thus was setling things aboue,
In other none, but him, she sets delight,
But he sets nought at all by Florimell:
And setst thy kingdome in the captiue harts
Formerly grounded, and fast setteled
Themselues to setten forth to straungers sight:
He pulleth downe, he setteth vp on hy;
From the vprising to the setting Sunne,
Their setting forth, in these few thousand yeares
Her proud foote setting, at his head did leuell,
And setting vp an Idole of his owne,
And setting on his steede, her did sustaine
At last about the setting of the Sunne,
So deepe did settle in her gratious thought,
And settle patience in so furious heat?
Ne suffred sleepe to settle in his brest.
That all on vprore from her settled seat
So settled he his kingdome, and confirmd his right.
Vntill he had her settled in her raine,
For seuen great heads out of his body grew,
In which seuen Bead-men that had vowed all
The first and chiefest of the seuen, whose care
When with one sword seuen knights I brought to end,
And seuen times dipped in the bitter waue
Seuen yeares this wize they vs besieged haue,
Proportioned equally by seuen and nine;
Which had seuen hundred yeares this scepter borne,
Euen seuen hundred Princes, which maintaynd
Seuen of the same against the Castle gate,
Suffred, these seuen monethes day in secret den
Seuen moneths he so her kept in bitter smart,
Seuen Knights one after other as they came:
One of the worlds seuen wonders sayd to bee,
There did this lucklesse mayd seuen months abide,
His seuenfold teme behind the stedfast starre,
Vpon this dreadfull Beast with seuenfold head
That seuen-fold shield, which he from Guyon brought
And on his shield enueloped seuenfold
Of his seuenfolded shield away it tooke,
By muddy shore of broad seuen-mouthed Nile,
Euen seuenteene goodly sonnes; which who had seene
Yet seuenteene yeares, but tall and faire of face
The seuenth now after death and buriall done,
Damon and Pythias whom death could not seuer;
Of nightly stelths and pillage seuerall,
The rest had seuerall offices assind,
Their sundry kings to do their homage seuerall.
So both tooke goodly leaue, and parted seuerall.
And seuerall deceipts, but all in vaine:
And each his sundrie sheepe with seuerall care
Which Seuerne now from Logris doth depart:
Which of her name now Seuerne men do call:
And them vnwares besides the Seuerne did enclose.
No not the stately Seuerne grudg'd at all,
Fought with Seuerus, and him ouerthrew;
Since errant armes to sew he first began;
Wherefore if me thou deigne to serue and sew,
To her, to whom the heauens do serue and sew?
That with the wind, contrary courses sew,
To Proteus selfe to sew she thought it vaine,
To spin, to card, to sew, to wash, to wring;
That from henceforth he meanes no more to sew
Yet ceast he not to sew and all waies proue,
And that it was a knight, which now her sewd,
Both worthie is for to be sewd vnto,
He did her seruice dewtifull, and sewed
In sewing deeds of armes, my liues and labours end.
Sewing the Blatant beast, which I forbore
This gentle knight, from sewing his first quest,
Through all this realme, the glorie of her sex,
All ignoraunt of her contrary sex,
So he surpassed his sex masculine,
Who for to hide her fained sex the better,
(For she her sexe vnder that straunge purport
Who by self-feeling of her feeble sexe,
Boue all her sexe that euer yet was seene;
That shamefull Hag, the slaunder of her sexe,
His shackles emptie left, him selfe escaped cleene.
The forward footing for an hidden shade:
A litle glooming light, much like a shade,
For the coole shade him thither hastly got:
Who all that while lay hid in secret shade:
